      <exercise id="fs-id1395614" type="problem-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1395616">
      <para id="import-auto-id1165298717342">Show that the acceleration of any object down an incline where friction behaves simply (that is, where <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{f rSub { size 8{k} } =μ rSub { size 8{k} } N} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) is <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi>g</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mrow><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">).</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{a=g \( "sin"θ - μ rSub { size 8{k} } "cos"θ \) } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> Note that the acceleration is independent of mass and reduces to the expression found in the previous problem when friction becomes negligibly small <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>k</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">).</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ \( μ rSub { size 8{k} } =0 \)  "." } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para></problem></exercise>
